I appreciate that you told me why you downvoted - it's very helpful.

So, elephant in the room: there are a bunch of different canons regarding how often D-Class are terminated, ranging from  based on this sentiment?

My personal canon is far on the  side, but I also like to think that the Foundation pretends that it terminates D-Class more than it really does. It's a useful psychological tool, to convince the D-Class that they need perfect behavior to avoid their dirt-nap: otherwise they'd need to work a lot harder to keep people in line.

On the other hand, there are occasionally going to be D-Class that have outlived their usefullness, either due to consistently uncontrollable behavior across multiple amnestic cycles, terminal diseases which will be uneconomical to treat and render the individual useless for tests, or expensive injuries incurred during testing. When a test requires a D-Class for whom the death date can be confidently known, either because the test will cause fatal symptoms or has predictive or retrocausal effects which the test is designed to establish the limits of, this smaller pool of schedulable D-Class can be used.

Back to this SCP, I hinted at the above backstory when I talked about needing D-Class whose terminations have been scheduled: this was intended to suggest, because the instructions were necessary in the first place, that this was an unusual or difficult requirement. I think I did a bad job of communicating this (and I think in my zeal to have a spooky  I unintentionally went too far), so I've made an edit which will hopefully make both of us happier.

And, heck, maybe you'll still hate it. Fair's fair. In any case, thanks for the feedback. :)







